[1] Wisconsin (Marathon County)
Date: Tue 17 Apr 2012
Source: Wausau (WI) Daily Herald [edited]
http://www.wausaudailyherald.com/article/20120417/WDH0101/120417073/Whooping-cough-outbreak-hits-Wausau-area


North central Wisconsin is in the middle of an outbreak of pertussis, according to the Marathon County Health Department. "We're seeing more cases than we would normally expect this time of year," said Ruth Marx, epidemiologist with the department. "We're up past 100 confirmed cases."

The Health Department is working with area school districts: D.C. Everest, Wausau, Mosinee, Marathon and Newman Catholic, to help prevent the spread of the illness. Letters have been sent to parents of students who are classmates of children with whooping cough. If children who came in contact with others who have pertussis, commonly known as whooping cough, exhibit signs of cold symptoms, they should stay home and see a physician. People who are found to have whooping cough, and those who come in close contact with those who are ill, are prescribed a regimen of antibiotics.

Most healthy teens and adults can recover from the illness, Marx said. But it's particularly dangerous to babies 6 months or younger or those who have compromised immune systems. "It kills infants," Marx said. "Infants haven't received a full series of immunizations until they're 6 months old."

